[[Image:macule.svg|thumb|150px|right|Macules]]

A '''macule''' is a change in skin color, without elevation or depression and, therefore, nonpalpable, well or ill-defined<ref name="fitz">Wolff, Klaus; Johnson, Richard; Suurmond, Dick (2005). Fitzpatrick's Color Atlas and Synopsis of Clinical Dermatology (5th ed.). McGraw-Hill. ISBN 0-07-144019-4.</ref>, variously sized but, by convention, less than one centimeter in diameter at the widest point.<ref name="Andrews">James, William; Berger, Timothy; Elston, Dirk (2005) ''Andrews' Diseases of the Skin: Clinical Dermatology'' (10th ed.). Saunders. Page 15. ISBN 0721629210.</ref>  This skin lesion is recognizable due to the color difference compared with the surrounding normal skin<ref name="Lookingbill">Marks, James G; Miller, Jeffery (2006). ''Lookingbill and Marks' Principles of Dermatology'' (4th ed.). Elsevier Inc. ISBN 1-4160-3185-5.</ref>, and may be of any color, white, blue, or red for example.<ref name="Andrews" />  Diseases of the skin that present with maculae include [[vitiligo]], [[melasma]], and [[junctional nevus|junctional nevi]].<ref name="fitz" />

